Manual plan: Workspace sidebar tab

Goal

Expose Drawing workspace as its own sidebar item. No changes to compare logic, hooks, or API routes—only navigation + remembering where the user last worked.

The canonical route already exists in [client/src/App.tsx](client/src/App.tsx):

 /projects/:projectId/drawings/:drawingId/workspace



Step 1: Choose storage and key





Storage: Prefer sessionStorage if “come back” should be per browser tab; use localStorage if it should survive new tabs and browser restarts.



Key: a single app-specific string, e.g. qcqa:lastDrawingWorkspace.



Value: the full return path, including query string if you rely on it for selection (e.g.  /projects/2/drawings/3/workspace?subDrawingId=5 — only include params your app actually uses; see [useWorkspaceSelectionQueryParams](client/src/hooks/use_workspace_selection_query_params.ts)).



Step 2: Write the path when the user is on the workspace page

Where: [client/src/pages/drawing_workspace.tsx](client/src/pages/drawing_workspace.tsx).

When: After you know projectId and drawingId are valid (the same place you already gate before rendering DrawingWorkspaceBody, or inside DrawingWorkspaceBody with a useEffect).

Logic (manual):





Import useLocation from wouter if not already available in that module.



In a useEffect, depend on [location, projectId, drawingId] (or useLocation()’s full string + search).



Compute: const path = ${pathname}${search}`` (wouter’s location is often pathname-only; use window.location.search if you need the query).



storage.setItem(KEY, path).

Optional: also store projectId under qcqa:lastProjectId as a number string for a smarter fallback (see Step 4).



Step 3: Add the sidebar item

Where: [client/src/components/app-sidebar.tsx](client/src/components/app-sidebar.tsx).

Changes:





Import an icon (e.g. DraftingCompass or PanelsTopLeft from lucide-react).



At render time, read storage.getItem(KEY) into a variable (e.g. lastWorkspacePath).



Decide href for Workspace:





If lastWorkspacePath is non-empty and starts with /projects/ and includes /workspace, use it as Link href={lastWorkspacePath}.



Else use your fallback (Step 4).



Insert a new SidebarMenuItem in the main nav group (with Dashboard / Inspections / Objects), same pattern as existing items: SidebarMenuButton + Link + data-testid (e.g. nav-workspace).



Step 4: Fallback when nothing is stored

Pick one behavior and implement it in the sidebar:





A (simplest): href="/" so the user lands on the dashboard and opens a workspace from there again.



B: If you stored qcqa:lastProjectId, href={/projects/${id}/drawings} (opens picker for that project).



C: Disable the button when no lastWorkspacePath (no navigation; optional tooltip “Open a drawing workspace from the dashboard first”).



Step 5: Fix “active” state for Workspace

[app-sidebar.tsx](client/src/components/app-sidebar.tsx) currently uses exact match: isActive={location === item.url}.

Workspace will use a dynamic href, so for that row only use something like:





isActive={location.startsWith("/projects/") && location.includes("/drawings/") && location.includes("/workspace")}

—or compare location to the stored path if you normalize both the same way.



Step 6: Verify manually





Navigate to a workspace URL; confirm sessionStorage/localStorage contains the expected key/value.



Click Dashboard (or another tab); confirm URL changes.



Click Workspace; confirm you return to the same project/drawing (and query params if you stored them).



Open a new tab (if you used sessionStorage): confirm fallback behavior matches Step 4.



Optional: run client unit tests if you add data-testid and a test later.



